    <fr:title text="Boolean valuations and strong Kleene valuations">Boolean valuations and strong Kleene valuations</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Well, imagine we have some Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.
This must assign either the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> or the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> to every atomic sentence in the language, and then it must accord with the <fr:link href="/lectures/003N/" title="The Boolean structure" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/003N/" display-uri="003N" type="local">Boolean tables</fr:link> for every connective.</html:p>
    <html:p>What I want to point out now, though, is that this is actually enough for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> to <html:em>also</html:em> be a strong Kleene valuation.
To see this, start with atomic sentences.
The strong Kleene structure has the three values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>, and any way of assigning these values to the atomic sentences results in a strong Kleene valuation.
But if we take our Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, we can see that it does exactly this!
It just does it in a way that doesn't use the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex> for any atomic sentence.
</html:p>
    <html:p>Assigning legit values to the atomic sentences, of course, is not enough for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> to be a strong Kleene valuation.
It also has to assign values to compound sentences in a way that accords with the <fr:link href="/lectures/004G/" title="The strong Kleene structure" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/004G/" display-uri="004G" type="local">strong Kleene tables</fr:link>.
But have a look at the Boolean tables compared to the strong Kleene tables, connective by connective.</html:p>
    <html:p>For example, let's look at the tables for conjunction:</html:p>
