    </fr:tree>
    <html:p>Note that the Boolean table here lives inside the strong Kleene one.
That is, if we're calculating the value of a conjunction in accordance with the strong Kleene table, if both components take values from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}\}]]></fr:tex>, then the result will be exactly the same as if we were calculating the value in accordance with the Boolean table instead.</html:p>
    <html:p>And it's not just conjunction: this same relationship holds for all our other connectives.
As long as we start from just <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, we always get the same results in the strong Kleene structure that we get in the Boolean structure.
The difference between the structures only comes up when some sentence gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>: this can't happen in the Boolean structure.
But as long as all the atomic sentences get values <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then there can't be any divergence.</html:p>
    <html:p>This means that <html:em>every Boolean valuation is at the same time a strong Kleene valuation</html:em>.
That's an important link between the two structures.
</html:p>
