            <fr:title text="Classical counterexamples and K3 counterexamples">Classical counterexamples and K3 counterexamples</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>When we're asking about strength and weakness, we're asking about <html:em>which arguments</html:em> are in these logics.
And there's a sense in which we already know exactly which arguments are in these logics: an argument is in classical logic iff it has no counterexamples in the classical matrix; and an argument is in K3 iff it has no counterexamples in the K3 matrix.</html:p>
            <html:p>Our job here, then, is to draw these two ideas together, to make them comparable.
What relationships can we find between classical counterexamples and K3 counterexamples?
Here it can help to drill down to a more basic level: classical counterexamples are a certain kind of Boolean valuation, and K3 counterexamples are a certain kind of strong Kleene valuation.
So what relationships can we find between Boolean valuations and strong Kleene valuations?</html:p>
