                <fr:title text="Back to counterexamples">Back to counterexamples</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>With that link in hand, we're ready to return to counterexamples, to see if we can find a connection between classical counterexamples and K3 counterexamples.</html:p>
                <html:p>Start by thinking: what is a <fr:link href="/lectures/004Y/" title="Counterexample in a matrix, logic determined by a matrix" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/004Y/" display-uri="004Y" type="local">classical counterexample to an argument</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex>?
It's a Boolean valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where:
<html:ul><html:li>for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>we also have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
                <html:p>Now, we've just seen that every Boolean valuation is also a strong Kleene valuation.
So imagine that we have some classical counterexample to some argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex>.
Is it a K3 counterexample to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> as well?
Since it's a classical counterexample, it's a Boolean valuation, so it's also a strong Kleene valuation, which is a start.
What does a strong Kleene valuation need to be like to be a K3 counterexample to this argument?
It needs to give:
<html:ul><html:li>for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>, we have either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(B) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, and</html:li>
<html:li>we also have either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
                <html:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is a classical counterexample to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex>, then, it is <html:em>also</html:em> a K3 counterexample to that same argument: it brings all the premises to the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, which is designated in both matrices, and it brings the conclusion to the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, which is undesignated in both matrices.
So <html:em>every classical counterexample to an argument is at the same time a K3 counterexample to that argument as well.</html:em></html:p>
